WEBVTT

00:06.173 --> 00:09.259
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.259 --> 00:12.054
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:12.054 --> 00:15.057
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:15.057 --> 00:16.433
<i>- My name is Connor.</i>

00:16.433 --> 00:17.726
I've been bladesmithing

00:17.726 --> 00:19.144
for almost four years.

00:19.144 --> 00:21.522
And I'm from
Edison, New Jersey.

00:21.522 --> 00:23.148
Edison is the town

00:23.148 --> 00:25.984
where Thomas Edison
invented the light bulb.

00:25.984 --> 00:27.361
Ta-da.

00:27.361 --> 00:29.071
<i>- My name's Brian Weaver.</i>

00:29.071 --> 00:31.031
Over the years,
I've dabbled in a few things.

00:31.031 --> 00:33.450
<i>I've been a jeweler,</i>
<i>a wood carver.</i>

00:33.450 --> 00:34.618
<i>I do leather work.</i>

00:34.618 --> 00:35.619
I do metal sculptures,

00:35.619 --> 00:37.538
<i>bladesmithing.</i>

00:37.538 --> 00:39.748
I fence competitively
and have been a martial artist

00:39.748 --> 00:42.876
and studied iaido.

00:42.876 --> 00:44.586
<i>- My name is Curtis Haaland.</i>

00:44.586 --> 00:46.255
<i>I'm 21 years old.</i>

00:46.255 --> 00:48.298
I think that
I will do pretty well

00:48.298 --> 00:50.759
going into this competition,
because a few years ago,

00:50.759 --> 00:52.970
I started learning
from Burt Foster.

00:52.970 --> 00:55.722
<i>He's a Mastersmith</i>
<i>and "Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

00:55.722 --> 00:57.224
<i>I've always loved knives.</i>

00:57.224 --> 00:58.642
<i>I always have a big knife</i>

00:58.642 --> 01:00.102
hanging off the side
of my belt,

01:00.102 --> 01:03.605
ready to use on,
you know, wood or a bear.

01:03.605 --> 01:05.107
Just whip it out.

01:05.107 --> 01:06.942
<i>- My name is Marc Setzer,</i>

01:06.942 --> 01:08.527
<i>I'm from Albany, Ohio,</i>
<i>and I'm 34 years old.</i>

01:08.527 --> 01:10.237
I have kind of a unique résumé.

01:10.237 --> 01:12.864
I'm a full-time farrier,
part-time bus driver,

01:12.864 --> 01:15.993
so I can deal with
high-stress situations.

01:15.993 --> 01:19.871
I mean, have you ever driven
a bus full of kids?

01:19.871 --> 01:22.583
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:22.583 --> 01:24.334
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:24.334 --> 01:25.961
You're here
for three timed rounds

01:25.961 --> 01:27.588
of edged weapon making
competition,

01:27.588 --> 01:29.590
specifically designed
to test every aspect

01:29.590 --> 01:31.174
of your capabilities,

01:31.174 --> 01:33.343
all in front of our panel
of expert judges.

01:33.343 --> 01:34.970
These are the men who decide
which of you will be

01:34.970 --> 01:36.930
our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:36.930 --> 01:39.266
and leave here with a check
for $10,000.

01:39.266 --> 01:40.976
So let's meet them now.

01:40.976 --> 01:43.979
Up first,
ABS Mastersmith J. Neilson.

01:43.979 --> 01:47.858
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker.

01:47.858 --> 01:50.652
Edged weapons specialist
Doug Marcaida.

01:50.652 --> 01:52.154
<i>[cymbal shimmering]</i>

01:52.154 --> 01:53.530
On your anvils is a cloth.

01:53.530 --> 01:55.365
Go ahead and lift that up.

01:55.365 --> 01:57.826
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:57.826 --> 02:00.454
That is a 3-inch-diameter
sphere

02:00.454 --> 02:03.957
of 52-100 high-carbon
chromium steel.

02:03.957 --> 02:07.377
- I'm nervous because
I've never used 52-100 steel,

02:07.377 --> 02:10.172
and forging is
a very violent process,

02:10.172 --> 02:11.840
<i>so if you don't know</i>
<i>how it acts</i>

02:11.840 --> 02:14.301
<i>during that type of pressure,</i>

02:14.301 --> 02:16.511
<i>then anything could happen.</i>

02:16.511 --> 02:18.764
- Gentlemen,
your job in the first round

02:18.764 --> 02:20.807
is to take
that steel ball bearing

02:20.807 --> 02:24.353
and forge it into a signature
blade in your signature style.

02:24.353 --> 02:25.896
Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:25.896 --> 02:27.648
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:27.648 --> 02:29.358
to turn them into
fully functional weapons.

02:29.358 --> 02:31.652
They will then be tested
for strength and durability

02:31.652 --> 02:33.695
in an antler chop.

02:33.695 --> 02:36.406
And then we'll be testing them
for edge retention

02:36.406 --> 02:38.617
in a leather bag slice.

02:38.617 --> 02:40.243
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:40.243 --> 02:44.081
Your ten-minute design window
starts now.

02:44.081 --> 02:46.500
While these bladesmiths
are designing these knives,

02:46.500 --> 02:49.169
the idea is to design
for the test at hand.

02:49.169 --> 02:51.672
- Well, we've seen what an
antler chop can do to a knife.

02:51.672 --> 02:53.465
That can eat a knife up
like crazy.

02:53.465 --> 02:56.551
- Well, they could work that
in doing a lighter knife.

02:56.551 --> 02:57.886
- You don't need
to chop through it.

02:57.886 --> 03:00.597
You just need to not
damage the blade.

03:00.597 --> 03:02.432
- So by having less mass
in the blade,

03:02.432 --> 03:04.309
you're really hitting
with a lot less force.

03:04.309 --> 03:06.478
It's just not gonna affect
the knife nearly as much.

03:06.478 --> 03:08.480
- Yeah, but I'm gonna try
and chop through the antler.

03:08.480 --> 03:10.440
[laughter]
- That's true, yeah.

03:10.440 --> 03:12.484
I kinda forgot the J. factor.

03:12.484 --> 03:14.319
<i>- The knife I'm gonna make</i>
<i>is a competition</i>

03:14.319 --> 03:17.197
chopper/bolo
with a slight recurve.

03:17.197 --> 03:18.865
<i>And I'm just gonna</i>
<i>keep it simple.</i>

03:18.865 --> 03:21.827
<i>I like to make blades</i>
<i>that could be used</i>

03:21.827 --> 03:25.205
to either chop down a tree
or open up a beer bottle, so...

03:25.205 --> 03:27.332
- My design is a camp knife.

03:27.332 --> 03:29.334
It's big. It's a chopper.

03:29.334 --> 03:31.628
<i>I need something</i>
<i>that's gonna hold an edge</i>

03:31.628 --> 03:33.672
<i>during that chopping test.</i>

03:33.672 --> 03:37.426
- Curtis is a pupil of a former
"Forged in Fire" champion.

03:37.426 --> 03:39.136
Burt Foster.
- Yep.

03:39.136 --> 03:41.930
- Doug, does the mentorship
matter in competition?

03:41.930 --> 03:43.640
- Absolutely.
He should have one up,

03:43.640 --> 03:46.017
because Burt's been in
this competition twice.

03:46.017 --> 03:47.936
<i>One of the best blades I ever</i>
<i>wielded was made by Burt.</i>

03:47.936 --> 03:49.729
<i>- That was the Shotel,</i>
<i>correct?</i>

03:49.729 --> 03:51.731
Oh, man, I still remember
how beautiful that thing is.

03:51.731 --> 03:54.234
- That thing just cut
through the air.

03:54.234 --> 03:57.320
- The signature blade
that I'm drawing is a comp-B.

03:57.320 --> 03:59.281
<i>It means competition bowie.</i>

03:59.281 --> 04:02.200
I'm gonna steal this soapstone,
just 'cause.

04:02.200 --> 04:05.745
I've had a nickname
for quite some time.

04:05.745 --> 04:07.581
Condor.

04:07.581 --> 04:09.124
<i>Partially because</i>
<i>it rhymes with Connor,</i>

04:09.124 --> 04:11.001
but also because
it's a type of vulture

04:11.001 --> 04:12.711
with a very long wingspan.

04:12.711 --> 04:14.754
And, uh, well...

04:14.754 --> 04:17.424
I've got very long arms.

04:17.424 --> 04:20.719
Did anybody find
a loose pen cap?

04:20.719 --> 04:21.970
Where's my pen cap?

04:21.970 --> 04:24.055
- Is it in your mouth?
- No.

04:24.055 --> 04:25.724
Is it in my hair?

04:25.724 --> 04:27.392
- What I'm gonna make
is a loose interpretation

04:27.392 --> 04:29.186
of a camp knife.

04:29.186 --> 04:30.645
<i>It's got a little bit</i>
<i>of a curve to it,</i>

04:30.645 --> 04:31.938
<i>but it'll stand up</i>
<i>to the chop.</i>

04:31.938 --> 04:34.107
As far as my strategy goes...

04:34.107 --> 04:37.319
<i>[rock music]</i>

04:37.319 --> 04:39.029
Well, quite honestly,
I'd be bull[bleep] you

04:39.029 --> 04:41.364
if I said I had a strategy.

04:41.364 --> 04:42.741
Yeah.

04:42.741 --> 04:44.451
- Your design period is closed.

04:44.451 --> 04:47.162
Your three-hour forge time
starts... now.

04:47.162 --> 04:49.372
<i>[exciting music]</i>

04:49.372 --> 04:51.917
- That's a big ball bearing.

04:51.917 --> 04:54.377
- You got 3 inches
of chromium steel.

04:54.377 --> 04:57.506
It needs to be forged
at a high temperature.

04:57.506 --> 04:59.132
- How much time
do you think these guys

04:59.132 --> 05:01.009
are having to wait out

05:01.009 --> 05:03.345
while their ball bearings
get hot?

05:03.345 --> 05:04.638
- Oh, I'd give it
at least 15 minutes.

05:04.638 --> 05:06.056
- At least 15 minutes?
- Yeah.

05:06.056 --> 05:07.849
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:07.849 --> 05:09.851
<i>- My strategy</i>
<i>is to immediately</i>

05:09.851 --> 05:11.645
<i>get a handle welded on,</i>

05:11.645 --> 05:14.981
'cause ball bearings are not
easy to hold with tongs.

05:14.981 --> 05:17.359
- I wanna see these guys
start boxing up these forges,

05:17.359 --> 05:18.777
closing up these ends.

05:18.777 --> 05:20.153
That way,
you can build up more heat

05:20.153 --> 05:21.947
in those ball bearings faster.

05:21.947 --> 05:24.199
- It's a waiting game
of patience.

05:24.199 --> 05:25.325
- Heat for me!

05:25.325 --> 05:27.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:27.577 --> 05:29.162
<i>- The clock's ticking.</i>

05:29.162 --> 05:30.497
<i>I gotta get</i>
<i>this big chunk of steel</i>

05:30.497 --> 05:32.707
in the forge
as fast as possible.

05:32.707 --> 05:35.585
<i>I wanna get to the billet</i>
<i>stage as fast as I can.</i>

05:35.585 --> 05:38.129
Half the battle is
getting that thing hot.

05:38.129 --> 05:40.757
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.
That's not hot enough.

05:40.757 --> 05:42.801
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:42.801 --> 05:45.554
- So Marc needs to pay
attention to getting it hot.

05:45.554 --> 05:47.639
Like, right now,
it's not moving.

05:47.639 --> 05:49.850
- I've gotta figure out
how to get this chunk of steel

05:49.850 --> 05:51.935
<i>hot enough to move it.</i>

05:51.935 --> 05:53.311
- Look at his forge, it's open.

05:53.311 --> 05:55.480
He's not blocking it up
all the way.

05:55.480 --> 05:57.357
- Connor's got the whole
back end blocked off,

05:57.357 --> 05:59.943
whereas Marc just took
one brick and stuck it inside,

05:59.943 --> 06:03.238
so it's still that whole open
area around that firebrick.

06:03.238 --> 06:05.156
- There's a lot of heat
escaping out of the back there.

06:05.156 --> 06:06.533
- Yep.

06:06.533 --> 06:08.535
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:08.535 --> 06:10.078
- Ball bearings,
they have to be heated up

06:10.078 --> 06:12.205
all the way through,
like bright red, right?

06:12.205 --> 06:13.832
- Oh, yeah,
you want it glowing.

06:13.832 --> 06:15.250
- And we've seen before

06:15.250 --> 06:16.459
where if you start
pounding on it,

06:16.459 --> 06:18.003
and the cul-de-sac disappears,

06:18.003 --> 06:19.754
that's where the stress
fractures come in.

06:19.754 --> 06:21.840
- I'm thinking the rebar
is probably gonna melt

06:21.840 --> 06:23.466
before the ball bearing
gets hot.

06:23.466 --> 06:25.552
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:25.552 --> 06:28.138
<i>This is a big ball</i>
<i>of very hard steel,</i>

06:28.138 --> 06:29.764
and you put something like that
into a forge,

06:29.764 --> 06:32.017
it's gonna take a long time
to heat up.

06:32.017 --> 06:35.312
<i>And, I mean, let's face it,</i>
<i>I have a clock ticking away,</i>

06:35.312 --> 06:37.188
tapping you on the shoulder
every few seconds.

06:37.188 --> 06:40.191
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:40.191 --> 06:42.319
- I've used this type
of power hammer before.

06:42.319 --> 06:44.404
<i>Burt Foster has one.</i>

06:44.404 --> 06:46.781
I feel very confident
that I can get a blade

06:46.781 --> 06:48.199
<i>very, very quickly.</i>

06:48.199 --> 06:50.702
- Curtis getting a long run
on Big Blue.

06:50.702 --> 06:52.662
[machine press banging]

06:52.662 --> 06:54.706
- I can dance to that tune.

06:54.706 --> 06:57.375
[banging continues]

07:00.128 --> 07:02.172
- You know, we're talking a lot
about this initial heat.

07:02.172 --> 07:03.548
I think what's gonna
be really telling

07:03.548 --> 07:05.300
is who keeps it working.

07:05.300 --> 07:06.426
- What you really
don't wanna do

07:06.426 --> 07:08.011
is work it till it's cold.

07:08.011 --> 07:10.430
You wanna work it
till it starts losing color.

07:10.430 --> 07:12.432
Doesn't drop temperature
too much.

07:12.432 --> 07:14.309
Get it back in the forge
so it reheats quicker.

07:14.309 --> 07:16.978
<i>- It does have to be hot</i>
<i>for it to move efficiently</i>

07:16.978 --> 07:19.147
and for it to keep
from cracking.

07:19.147 --> 07:20.690
A little bit more time.

07:20.690 --> 07:22.025
- It looks like,
now that Curtis

07:22.025 --> 07:24.361
has got his steel
a lot thinner,

07:24.361 --> 07:25.904
he's picking up heat faster

07:25.904 --> 07:28.281
and able to move the metal
more quickly.

07:28.281 --> 07:30.742
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:30.742 --> 07:34.371
Connor has taken
that 3-inch ball bearing

07:34.371 --> 07:37.666
and, in a little bit
over 30 minutes,

07:37.666 --> 07:39.668
turned it into a billet.

07:39.668 --> 07:41.878
- He's doing great work.

07:41.878 --> 07:43.713
- I'd describe the speed
that I work at as normal.

07:43.713 --> 07:47.050
[chuckles] But, of course,
that's because it's me.

07:47.050 --> 07:49.177
- Connor just formed
the tip on his blade.

07:49.177 --> 07:52.013
- I figured
that's what he was doing.

07:52.013 --> 07:54.099
- I don't know
what he's doing right now.

07:54.099 --> 07:55.975
- I haven't a clue.

07:55.975 --> 07:58.395
- He's putting water...

07:58.395 --> 08:00.063
on things.

08:00.063 --> 08:02.315
He's blessing everything
in the Forge,

08:02.315 --> 08:05.610
the blade, the vise.

08:05.610 --> 08:07.570
<i>- My blade is really hot,</i>

08:07.570 --> 08:10.365
<i>so I like to splash water</i>
<i>onto the back of it</i>

08:10.365 --> 08:12.033
and watch it steam off.

08:12.033 --> 08:14.703
But also I do it
partially for fun.

08:14.703 --> 08:17.497
- In nomine Patris et Filii
et Spiritus Sancti.

08:17.497 --> 08:19.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:19.249 --> 08:21.334
- Bladesmiths!

08:21.334 --> 08:23.503
You have only two hours
remaining to finish your work!

08:23.503 --> 08:26.214
- I'm worried about Marc.
- Yeah.

08:26.214 --> 08:28.883
Marc's been pulling it out,
where it's still, like,

08:28.883 --> 08:30.510
bright red but not yellow.

08:30.510 --> 08:31.428
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:33.430 --> 08:35.348
[bleep].

08:35.348 --> 08:38.184
It just seems like my forge
is burning a little--

08:38.184 --> 08:39.811
not quite as hot as

08:39.811 --> 08:42.021
maybe my forge at home
is used to.

08:42.021 --> 08:44.399
Sometimes I'm swinging
a hammer on cold steel.

08:44.399 --> 08:45.900
<i>I really don't want that.</i>

08:45.900 --> 08:47.819
That's how you get cracks
and weak spots.

08:47.819 --> 08:49.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:49.696 --> 08:51.656
[bleep].

08:51.656 --> 08:53.366
Pressure really doesn't
bother me most of the time.

08:53.366 --> 08:56.745
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:56.745 --> 08:59.622
[bleep].

08:59.622 --> 09:00.832
It's bothering me now.

09:00.832 --> 09:02.042
Can't get a good grip.

09:02.042 --> 09:04.210
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:04.210 --> 09:05.670
- Things are starting
to get in a groove now.

09:05.670 --> 09:07.630
<i>The metal's</i>
<i>the thickness I need.</i>

09:07.630 --> 09:09.632
<i>And I'm gonna go back</i>
<i>to my comfort zone,</i>

09:09.632 --> 09:11.801
where I'm working on the anvil

09:11.801 --> 09:14.220
and moving the metal
how I'm used to moving.

09:14.220 --> 09:16.222
- Brian's just moving
right along.

09:16.222 --> 09:17.974
He's got his blade all shaped.

09:17.974 --> 09:19.434
- Feeling pretty good about it.

09:19.434 --> 09:21.061
I'm gonna establish
some finger welds

09:21.061 --> 09:22.979
<i>on the handle of the knife,</i>

09:22.979 --> 09:25.065
'cause I know one of the things
the judges look for

09:25.065 --> 09:26.858
is how comfortable
it is in your hand.

09:26.858 --> 09:28.485
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:28.485 --> 09:31.654
- My favorite shape right now
is Curtis.

09:31.654 --> 09:34.532
He's got that nice upswept tip.

09:34.532 --> 09:35.617
- It looks like he added
a little bit of

09:35.617 --> 09:37.911
a recurve to it too.

09:37.911 --> 09:39.954
- I've got the blade shaped
to where I need it to be.

09:39.954 --> 09:43.416
I know I have enough time
to put holes in and quench.

09:43.416 --> 09:45.376
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:45.376 --> 09:48.129
- Connor's starting to get
his blade back into the forge,

09:48.129 --> 09:50.882
get it up to temperature
for the quench.

09:50.882 --> 09:53.802
<i>- The most important test in</i>
<i>consideration for this blade</i>

09:53.802 --> 09:56.471
<i>is definitely the antler chop,</i>

09:56.471 --> 09:58.348
so I decided to do
an edge quench...

09:58.348 --> 10:00.683
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:00.683 --> 10:02.602
<i>And the reason why I do that</i>
<i>is because</i>

10:02.602 --> 10:05.396
<i>it leaves the edge</i>
<i>really screamin' hard</i>

10:05.396 --> 10:07.982
<i>but allows for a very soft</i>
<i>and cushioning body,</i>

10:07.982 --> 10:10.193
able to absorb impact.

10:10.193 --> 10:12.779
Rather uneventful.
No fire, no explosions.

10:12.779 --> 10:14.656
- Connor did the edge quench,
which was good,

10:14.656 --> 10:17.242
but it was just maybe
a half an inch of that edge,

10:17.242 --> 10:18.451
and it looked more red
than orange.

10:18.451 --> 10:20.078
- Yeah.

10:20.078 --> 10:21.746
- I've sort of kind of
ran out of things to do,

10:21.746 --> 10:23.248
other than make it look pretty.

10:23.248 --> 10:25.083
Whoa. [blows]
That was unexpected.

10:25.083 --> 10:27.168
Might as well
just drill the holes.

10:27.168 --> 10:29.087
- This is what I like to see.

10:29.087 --> 10:30.672
I like to see a smith

10:30.672 --> 10:32.465
setting themselves up
for round two.

10:32.465 --> 10:34.467
- Yeah.

10:34.467 --> 10:36.344
<i>- I have a bit of an issue.</i>

10:36.344 --> 10:39.639
Clamping it into the vise,
it won't hold on straight,

10:39.639 --> 10:42.058
<i>so I decided to make</i>
<i>a bit of a spacer.</i>

10:42.058 --> 10:44.853
- Connor,
what are you doing with that?

10:44.853 --> 10:47.021
- I'm making a spacer
for the vise.

10:47.021 --> 10:49.190
- Out of our wire brush?

10:49.190 --> 10:50.733
- Yeah.

10:50.733 --> 10:52.944
It was brand-new.
I wanted to ruin it.

10:52.944 --> 10:54.612
- There's some wood
right there, but whatever.

10:54.612 --> 10:56.823
- Now the vise won't slip.

10:56.823 --> 10:58.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:58.741 --> 11:00.952
- Thirty minutes, bladesmiths!

11:00.952 --> 11:03.121
<i>- I've got the basic shape.</i>

11:03.121 --> 11:05.165
<i>Right now, it kinda looks like</i>
<i>a pregnant letter opener,</i>

11:05.165 --> 11:07.750
a really, really big
pregnant letter opener.

11:07.750 --> 11:09.169
Geesh.

11:09.169 --> 11:10.962
<i>But I don't have</i>
<i>much time left.</i>

11:10.962 --> 11:12.672
I'm kinda upset
about the clock.

11:12.672 --> 11:14.716
I think it's moving faster
than it should.

11:14.716 --> 11:16.301
I need to get this quench done.

11:16.301 --> 11:17.927
- You can make that blade
as big

11:17.927 --> 11:19.596
and as thick as you want.

11:19.596 --> 11:20.889
If there's a stress fracture
in there,

11:20.889 --> 11:22.515
it's gonna break,
no matter what.

11:22.515 --> 11:27.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:27.854 --> 11:29.022
- Whoa!
both: Oh!

11:29.022 --> 11:30.440
- [bleep].

11:30.440 --> 11:32.066
Uh...

11:32.066 --> 11:35.195
I dropped my blade
into the quench tank.

11:35.195 --> 11:36.863
- Oh, man.

11:36.863 --> 11:37.989
<i>- If my blade's at the bottom</i>

11:37.989 --> 11:39.449
<i>of that tank in two pieces,</i>

11:39.449 --> 11:40.950
I'll be going home.

11:40.950 --> 11:43.976
<i>[tense music]</i>

11:48.814 --> 11:50.319
<i>[met</i>
- Oh, no.

11:50.319 --> 11:52.446
- That oil's hot, and you don't
wanna burn your hands.

11:52.446 --> 11:53.405
- Oof.

11:53.405 --> 11:54.531
<i>- I've gotta dive</i>

11:54.531 --> 11:55.741
elbow-deep into this hot oil

11:55.741 --> 11:58.702
to try to find my blade.

12:03.499 --> 12:06.043
- There it is.
- [laughs]

12:06.043 --> 12:10.088
- I'm so glad
my blade is not in pieces.

12:10.088 --> 12:11.590
- It's not hard.

12:11.590 --> 12:13.050
- That does not sound
hard at all.

12:13.050 --> 12:14.760
- [bleep].

12:14.760 --> 12:16.345
<i>I'm completely</i>
<i>and totally heartbroken.</i>

12:16.345 --> 12:18.263
It's gotta go back in the fire.

12:18.263 --> 12:19.848
<i>If I don't get</i>
<i>this heat treat right,</i>

12:19.848 --> 12:21.767
I'm done.

12:21.767 --> 12:24.478
- We've got Curtis
getting ready to quench.

12:24.478 --> 12:27.314
- This 52-100 steel
is new steel to me,

12:27.314 --> 12:29.191
<i>and I'm worried</i>
<i>because it could take</i>

12:29.191 --> 12:32.694
a little more heat
than I'm used to.

12:32.694 --> 12:34.655
- Curtis in the quench.
- That's what I like to see.

12:34.655 --> 12:36.323
<i>[rock music]</i>

12:36.323 --> 12:38.700
- I'm happy with my quench.
I do a file test.

12:38.700 --> 12:41.954
I know that this blade is hard.

12:41.954 --> 12:43.288
You good, man.

12:43.288 --> 12:44.998
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:44.998 --> 12:46.875
- And here goes Brian.

12:46.875 --> 12:48.961
- And Brian's in.
- Brian's in the quench.

12:48.961 --> 12:51.004
<i>- Anything can go wrong</i>
<i>in the quench.</i>

12:51.004 --> 12:53.632
It's a hard steel,
we just moved it a bunch,

12:53.632 --> 12:56.134
<i>so this is make-or-break</i>
<i>right here.</i>

12:56.134 --> 12:58.220
You know, I'm keeping
my fingers crossed.

12:58.220 --> 13:00.597
[bleep].
- How's it looking?

13:00.597 --> 13:03.475
- I think I got a slight
little warp here at the end.

13:03.475 --> 13:05.602
- Pretty tough steel, I think.
- Yeah.

13:05.602 --> 13:08.855
If I can't get this warp out,
this could be game over.

13:08.855 --> 13:11.066
- Ten! Nine!

13:11.066 --> 13:12.693
Eight! Seven!

13:12.693 --> 13:14.861
Six! Five!

13:14.861 --> 13:16.488
Four! Three!

13:16.488 --> 13:19.408
Two! One!

13:19.408 --> 13:21.785
Bladesmiths, drop your tools,
shut down your machines.

13:21.785 --> 13:24.371
This round is over.

13:24.371 --> 13:27.207
- Now that I have
a finished blade, I feel great.

13:27.207 --> 13:29.418
<i>My blade might not be</i>
<i>the prettiest one out here...</i>

13:29.418 --> 13:31.378
Dang, that thing's ugly.

13:31.378 --> 13:33.505
<i>But it's hardened,</i>
<i>it fits all the parameters.</i>

13:33.505 --> 13:36.174
I think I've accomplished
my goals.

13:36.174 --> 13:37.676
<i>[cymbal shimmering]</i>

13:37.676 --> 13:39.261
- Bladesmiths,
in three short hours,

13:39.261 --> 13:42.723
each of you has taken
a 3-inch-diameter sphere

13:42.723 --> 13:44.433
of 52-100 ball bearing steel

13:44.433 --> 13:46.184
and turned it into
a signature blade.

13:46.184 --> 13:47.811
Now it's time for the judges

13:47.811 --> 13:49.021
to take a closer look
at your work.

13:49.021 --> 13:50.605
Connor, you're up first.

13:50.605 --> 13:52.983
Please present your weapon
to the judges.

13:52.983 --> 13:54.818
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:54.818 --> 13:56.403
- Connor, I gotta say,

13:56.403 --> 13:58.071
I was extremely impressed
with the way you worked.

13:58.071 --> 14:00.073
You planned everything out.

14:00.073 --> 14:01.575
You're very precise
on everything.

14:01.575 --> 14:03.243
And it shows.

14:03.243 --> 14:04.786
I mean, you've got
a very nice piece here.

14:04.786 --> 14:06.621
My big concern was
during the heat treat.

14:06.621 --> 14:08.415
I'm not sure if you got
your edge to temperature.

14:08.415 --> 14:10.250
It's a bit softer
than it should be.

14:10.250 --> 14:11.710
Could end up with
a very serrated edge

14:11.710 --> 14:13.628
during the antler chop.

14:13.628 --> 14:15.547
I would definitely recommend
redoing the heat treat.

14:15.547 --> 14:17.132
- Brian, you're up next.

14:17.132 --> 14:19.301
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:19.301 --> 14:21.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:21.470 --> 14:23.555
- Brian,
your steel looks great,

14:23.555 --> 14:25.724
but the first thing
that catches my eye is this.

14:25.724 --> 14:28.852
Now you got basically
a hand-and-a-half handle here.

14:28.852 --> 14:31.563
And you've got...

14:31.563 --> 14:33.690
a warp in the blade,

14:33.690 --> 14:36.109
where your handle's
actually kicking out this way.

14:36.109 --> 14:39.363
And they got a little bit
of a twist right in here,

14:39.363 --> 14:40.822
<i>so your blade</i>
<i>during the heat treat</i>

14:40.822 --> 14:43.033
actually moved in
two different directions.

14:43.033 --> 14:44.951
- You're up, Curtis.

14:44.951 --> 14:46.411
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:46.411 --> 14:48.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:48.830 --> 14:51.666
- Curtis, yeah, man.
[chuckles]

14:51.666 --> 14:53.668
This looks like
a Jason Knight design,

14:53.668 --> 14:55.796
something that can chop
and stab.

14:55.796 --> 14:58.298
But that's a big handle
right there.

14:58.298 --> 15:00.384
If you move forward,
you will have to address that,

15:00.384 --> 15:02.844
because it's uncomfortable.
- Marc, you're up.

15:02.844 --> 15:05.263
Please present your work
to the judges.

15:05.263 --> 15:07.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:07.474 --> 15:09.393
<i>- You know, generally, I like</i>
<i>the shape of this blade.</i>

15:09.393 --> 15:11.603
I would like to see it
more refined.

15:11.603 --> 15:13.563
It's just, right now,
it's kinda unfinished

15:13.563 --> 15:15.107
and very heavy.

15:15.107 --> 15:17.275
- There's a lot of
steel here, man.

15:17.275 --> 15:19.361
And you were having a hard time
heating up that steel,

15:19.361 --> 15:21.655
and we can tell that
by all the lines

15:21.655 --> 15:23.240
<i>and stress fractures.</i>

15:23.240 --> 15:26.159
Those cracks are going
all the way through.

15:26.159 --> 15:27.202
That's a problem.

15:27.202 --> 15:29.371
<i>[cymbal shimmering]</i>

15:29.371 --> 15:32.040
- Bladesmiths, the judges
have made their final decision.

15:32.040 --> 15:34.668
The bladesmith leaving
the Forge is...

15:34.668 --> 15:38.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:38.130 --> 15:39.464
Marc.

15:39.464 --> 15:40.966
Your blade didn't make the cut.

15:40.966 --> 15:42.801
J. Neilson's
gonna tell you why.

15:42.801 --> 15:44.803
- You know, Marc,
the big thing is,

15:44.803 --> 15:46.847
you didn't block up your forge.

15:46.847 --> 15:49.850
You had a lot of airflow
going out the back, so...

15:49.850 --> 15:51.393
You had a hard time
moving that steel,

15:51.393 --> 15:53.437
and that took up
so much of the three hours,

15:53.437 --> 15:56.022
you didn't have enough time
to refine that blade very much.

15:56.022 --> 15:57.399
<i>Between having</i>
<i>the least finished blade</i>

15:57.399 --> 15:58.984
<i>and the stress fractures,</i>

15:58.984 --> 16:00.610
<i>that's why we're</i>
<i>sending you home.</i>

16:00.610 --> 16:02.571
- Marc,
please surrender your blade.

16:02.571 --> 16:06.074
- A little disappointed,
but I kinda saw it coming.

16:06.074 --> 16:10.162
<i>I wish the three remaining</i>
<i>smiths the best of luck.</i>

16:10.162 --> 16:11.913
I've got two little girls
and a beautiful wife

16:11.913 --> 16:13.540
<i>that are waiting</i>
<i>for me at home.</i>

16:13.540 --> 16:15.167
<i>They're proud of me.</i>

16:15.167 --> 16:16.543
I'm still standing,
and I'm still smiling,

16:16.543 --> 16:20.088
and they can't take that
away from me.

16:20.088 --> 16:21.923
- Bladesmiths, congratulations,

16:21.923 --> 16:23.800
you've made it to the second
round of this competition.

16:23.800 --> 16:25.343
In this round,

16:25.343 --> 16:26.928
you'll be attaching handles
to your blades

16:26.928 --> 16:28.847
to turn them into
fully functional weapons.

16:28.847 --> 16:31.016
They will then be tested
for strength and durability

16:31.016 --> 16:33.143
in that antler chop...

16:33.143 --> 16:36.855
and for edge retention
in a leather bag slice.

16:36.855 --> 16:38.773
In this particular round,

16:38.773 --> 16:41.359
you will only be allowed to use
all-natural materials:

16:41.359 --> 16:44.029
Wood, antler, bone,

16:44.029 --> 16:46.490
brass, and stainless steel
for guards and pins.

16:46.490 --> 16:47.908
You'll have three hours
to do this.

16:47.908 --> 16:50.994
Get ready,
because your time starts now.

16:50.994 --> 16:53.914
<i>[rock music]</i>

16:53.914 --> 16:57.459
Connor has already come away
with a block of natural wood.

16:57.459 --> 16:59.044
- It looks like Cocobolo
or something.

16:59.044 --> 17:01.505
- Cocobolo.
- The wood's a good choice.

17:01.505 --> 17:03.089
We've got some
pretty wide handles.

17:03.089 --> 17:05.091
A wide chunk of wood,

17:05.091 --> 17:07.802
it's easier to find something
that'll fit your profile.

17:07.802 --> 17:09.471
<i>- I take the wood,</i>
<i>put it on the band saw,</i>

17:09.471 --> 17:12.015
<i>and it's cutting very slowly,</i>

17:12.015 --> 17:14.059
but I just have to
muscle through it,

17:14.059 --> 17:16.394
<i>'cause it seems to be</i>
<i>the only tool on hand</i>

17:16.394 --> 17:19.231
<i>that can really cut through</i>
<i>in a somewhat straight line.</i>

17:19.231 --> 17:21.316
- You can see him twisting
and turning that saw.

17:21.316 --> 17:23.026
I mean,
he's all over the place.

17:23.026 --> 17:24.653
It looks like
he's trying to force it.

17:24.653 --> 17:28.782
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:28.782 --> 17:30.408
Curtis over here,

17:30.408 --> 17:32.452
he's worked on his tang
a little bit,

17:32.452 --> 17:35.789
trying to make it a little bit
more comfortable for our hands.

17:35.789 --> 17:37.874
- I always leave my tang
a little bit big

17:37.874 --> 17:40.710
<i>so that I have enough room</i>
<i>to grind anything out of it.</i>

17:40.710 --> 17:42.671
I have three hours.

17:42.671 --> 17:44.631
I feel very confident
that I can get everything done.

17:44.631 --> 17:46.299
- That's Darth Curtis.

17:46.299 --> 17:48.051
- Darth Curtis.
- [chuckles]

17:48.051 --> 17:50.053
How are you doing, Curtis?
[modulated breathing]

17:50.053 --> 17:52.097
[laughter]

17:52.097 --> 17:54.808
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:54.808 --> 17:56.643
<i>- First thing I have to do</i>
<i>is make that handle</i>

17:56.643 --> 17:59.145
a little bit more
reasonably sized.

17:59.145 --> 18:01.231
The second thing is,
I have to try to fix

18:01.231 --> 18:02.816
<i>the warp in my blade.</i>

18:02.816 --> 18:04.484
- So, Brian heading over
to the welder.

18:04.484 --> 18:06.862
He's removed the section
of his tang.

18:06.862 --> 18:08.738
He kept the flare,

18:08.738 --> 18:10.657
and he's gonna weld that flare
back on his tang.

18:10.657 --> 18:12.701
- That's awesome.
- That's a brilliant move.

18:12.701 --> 18:15.370
- With this kind of time,

18:15.370 --> 18:17.956
<i>I should be able to address</i>
<i>the judges' issues quickly,</i>

18:17.956 --> 18:19.916
<i>which leaves me with a very</i>
<i>comfortable amount of time</i>

18:19.916 --> 18:21.877
to ply the handle,

18:21.877 --> 18:25.505
make sure it's finished nicely
and fits nicely.

18:25.505 --> 18:27.299
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:27.299 --> 18:28.800
- I got a feeling
that Connor's not

18:28.800 --> 18:30.135
gonna do anything
about his blade.

18:30.135 --> 18:31.761
- That's a big mistake
right there.

18:31.761 --> 18:34.306
When you saw that we had
already an issue

18:34.306 --> 18:35.807
with the hardness of his blade,

18:35.807 --> 18:37.225
and we're gonna test it
on antlers?

18:37.225 --> 18:39.185
That's the first thing
I'd go and fix.

18:39.185 --> 18:40.812
- Take the rosebud,
heat that up,

18:40.812 --> 18:42.647
roll it through the oil,
and it's done.

18:42.647 --> 18:44.024
- Yep. Just take
the hot wrench to it...

18:44.024 --> 18:45.650
- You bet.
- Nice and easy.

18:45.650 --> 18:46.943
<i>- I'm not gonna touch</i>
<i>the heat treat.</i>

18:46.943 --> 18:48.820
<i>I don't want to re-harden it</i>

18:48.820 --> 18:50.447
and then have a blade
that's way too brittle.

18:52.407 --> 18:54.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:54.117 --> 18:55.911
- It's very calm
in here right now.

18:55.911 --> 18:57.621
Everybody's
really squared away.

18:57.621 --> 19:00.665
They're really moving
at a steady pace.

19:00.665 --> 19:02.208
- I'm not used to having
a relaxed atmosphere here.

19:02.208 --> 19:04.461
- Yeah.

19:04.461 --> 19:06.296
It's time to turn up the heat
in the Forge, what do you say?

19:06.296 --> 19:07.756
- Sounds good.
- I agree.

19:07.756 --> 19:10.884
- Bladesmiths!
One hour has elapsed!

19:10.884 --> 19:14.179
You now have only
one hour remaining

19:14.179 --> 19:15.305
to finish your work.

19:15.305 --> 19:17.223
That's right, gentlemen.

19:17.223 --> 19:18.308
We just dropped an hour
off the clock.

19:18.308 --> 19:20.310
Get to it.

19:20.310 --> 19:22.008
- Well, [bleep].

19:25.568 --> 19:26.824
- The thing is,
it's not necessarily

19:26.824 --> 19:29.368
that we've given them
a challenge physically.

19:29.368 --> 19:30.620
It's that mental challenge.

19:30.620 --> 19:32.330
Can they shift gears,

19:32.330 --> 19:34.373
move into high gear,
and get it done nicely?

19:34.373 --> 19:35.750
Or do they go into panic mode?

19:35.750 --> 19:38.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:38.711 --> 19:40.630
- Right now,
I've got the slabs cut.

19:40.630 --> 19:42.882
<i>I've got the handle prepped,</i>
<i>all flat, ready to go,</i>

19:42.882 --> 19:45.134
<i>and I need to start</i>
<i>shaping this handle.</i>

19:45.134 --> 19:47.094
- Brian over here,
he's set his pins in place,

19:47.094 --> 19:49.722
his epoxy, and he's just
painting them over right now.

19:49.722 --> 19:51.474
<i>[rock music]</i>

19:51.474 --> 19:53.017
- Time kinda compresses
the strategy,

19:53.017 --> 19:54.685
but, for me,
I'm not gonna change gears.

19:54.685 --> 19:56.812
<i>Quite honestly,</i>
<i>one of the reasons</i>

19:56.812 --> 19:59.398
<i>I'm doing this</i>
<i>is to challenge myself.</i>

19:59.398 --> 20:01.317
<i>I mean, this is why</i>
<i>we came here.</i>

20:01.317 --> 20:03.235
It's not, you know,
"Forged in Leisure."

20:03.235 --> 20:06.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:06.989 --> 20:09.033
- The only one really who was
taking their time was Curtis.

20:09.033 --> 20:11.577
He didn't work on his handle.
Now there he is.

20:11.577 --> 20:14.163
- Every time I work,
I have steps in my head.

20:14.163 --> 20:17.249
Now I have to figure out
a way to shift.

20:17.249 --> 20:19.418
<i>I need to cut these scales,</i>

20:19.418 --> 20:22.046
<i>put holes in, get them shaped,</i>

20:22.046 --> 20:24.131
get the transition
from the ricasso to the handle

20:24.131 --> 20:26.258
shaped so they're even.

20:26.258 --> 20:28.427
<i>I love pushing myself</i>

20:28.427 --> 20:30.429
<i>to do things faster, better.</i>

20:30.429 --> 20:31.806
I'm always up for a challenge.

20:31.806 --> 20:33.349
<i>[cymbal shimmering]</i>

20:33.349 --> 20:35.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:35.518 --> 20:37.895
- I don't have much time.

20:37.895 --> 20:40.523
This is really turning into
a mental challenge for me.

20:40.523 --> 20:42.858
- This is an interesting
challenge to overcome.

20:42.858 --> 20:46.237
I mean, to lose an hour
is a big deal.

20:46.237 --> 20:48.280
- I got to completely
redo my plan,

20:48.280 --> 20:51.701
<i>so I basically cut out</i>
<i>all of the last hour</i>

20:51.701 --> 20:53.869
and condensed as much as I can

20:53.869 --> 20:55.538
<i>with the handle making.</i>

20:55.538 --> 20:57.081
My mind is racing

20:57.081 --> 20:59.166
at about 1,000 miles an hour.

20:59.166 --> 21:01.293
- The pressure's amped up
a little bit more.

21:01.293 --> 21:03.504
- I've gotta get
this frickin' handle done.

21:03.504 --> 21:05.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:05.756 --> 21:08.008
- So Curtis is mixing up
some five-minute epoxy.

21:08.008 --> 21:09.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:09.719 --> 21:11.887
And that means he's ready
to put his scales on.

21:11.887 --> 21:13.848
<i>- I'm waiting on</i>
<i>the glue to dry,</i>

21:13.848 --> 21:15.975
but I don't have time
to watch glue dry.

21:15.975 --> 21:17.768
<i>I need to get stuff done.</i>

21:17.768 --> 21:20.271
- While Curtis's handle
is curing up,

21:20.271 --> 21:21.939
he's sharpening his blade.

21:21.939 --> 21:23.149
- That's not a bad idea.
- Yeah.

21:23.149 --> 21:25.151
<i>- I feel really good about it.</i>

21:25.151 --> 21:28.279
At this point, I can shape
a handle within ten minutes.

21:28.279 --> 21:31.449
This challenge, it isn't
against me and a competitor.

21:31.449 --> 21:34.368
<i>It's against myself</i>
<i>and my own personal abilities.</i>

21:34.368 --> 21:37.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:37.246 --> 21:39.081
- Connor's handle is on.

21:39.081 --> 21:41.250
He's sharpening his blade.

21:41.250 --> 21:44.003
I am so thoroughly impressed.

21:44.003 --> 21:46.297
Never have we taken time away.

21:46.297 --> 21:48.257
And I don't think
we've ever had smiths

21:48.257 --> 21:50.593
rise to the occasion
as a group,

21:50.593 --> 21:52.428
like these three smiths has.

21:52.428 --> 21:53.637
- I definitely planned
on having

21:53.637 --> 21:54.972
three hours instead of two.

21:54.972 --> 21:56.557
- [laughs]
Yeah.

21:56.557 --> 21:57.933
Yeah, that was the first thing
that went wrong.

21:57.933 --> 21:59.894
- Yeah.

21:59.894 --> 22:00.978
- I've got the handle
to the point

22:00.978 --> 22:02.730
where I'm comfortable with it.

22:02.730 --> 22:04.356
<i>I could do more,</i>
<i>but I've utilized</i>

22:04.356 --> 22:06.233
<i>the two hours to the best</i>
<i>of my abilities,</i>

22:06.233 --> 22:08.194
and I'm happy with it.

22:08.194 --> 22:10.321
- Ten! Nine!

22:10.321 --> 22:12.156
Eight! Seven!

22:12.156 --> 22:14.158
Six! Five!

22:14.158 --> 22:16.076
Four! Three!

22:16.076 --> 22:18.162
Two! One!

22:18.162 --> 22:20.122
Bladesmiths, drop your tools,
stop what you're doing.

22:20.122 --> 22:21.874
This round is over.

22:21.874 --> 22:23.167
- Yeah! Bravo!
- [whistles]

22:23.167 --> 22:24.877
- Good job, guys.
Good job, guys.

22:24.877 --> 22:26.796
- Bravo!

22:26.796 --> 22:28.839
- I'm extremely happy
with how the knife turned out.

22:28.839 --> 22:30.800
<i>I came into "Forged in Fire"</i>

22:30.800 --> 22:32.468
ready to face
whatever they threw at me.

22:32.468 --> 22:34.386
<i>I've done a knife</i>
<i>in five hours.</i>

22:34.386 --> 22:36.680
And now
it's in the judges' hands.

22:36.680 --> 22:38.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:38.474 --> 22:40.518
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to our strength test.

22:40.518 --> 22:42.520
This is the dreaded
antler chop.

22:42.520 --> 22:45.898
I'm gonna take these beautiful
signature blades that you did,

22:45.898 --> 22:49.276
and I'm gonna smash them
violently and repeatedly

22:49.276 --> 22:51.529
into these extremely
dense antlers.

22:51.529 --> 22:54.031
I don't really care what
your blades do to the antler.

22:54.031 --> 22:56.742
I wanna see what the antler's
gonna do to your blades.

22:56.742 --> 22:59.370
It's gonna be horrifying.

22:59.370 --> 23:00.746
I'm gonna love it.

23:00.746 --> 23:02.414
Connor, you're up first.
You ready?

23:02.414 --> 23:04.208
- Yeah, go and try
and break it.

23:04.208 --> 23:05.251
- Let's see
what we can do here.

23:05.251 --> 23:07.586
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:07.586 --> 23:09.672
<i>- I addressed the issues</i>

23:09.672 --> 23:11.382
<i>that the judges had</i>
<i>with my blade,</i>

23:11.382 --> 23:13.384
<i>other than the heat treat.</i>

23:13.384 --> 23:15.302
If it's too brittle,

23:15.302 --> 23:16.720
then I could be sending
a blade edge

23:16.720 --> 23:17.805
into somebody's eye.

23:17.805 --> 23:19.849
[exhaling rhythmically]

23:21.433 --> 23:24.353
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:24.353 --> 23:31.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:33.863 --> 23:35.739
Nice.

23:35.739 --> 23:36.991
- [groans softly]

23:36.991 --> 23:38.367
<i>[cymbal shimmering]</i>

23:38.367 --> 23:39.827
All right, Connor,
we got a couple

23:39.827 --> 23:41.120
of little problems here.

23:41.120 --> 23:42.621
Big one for me

23:42.621 --> 23:44.665
is this bird's beak
on the back end.

23:44.665 --> 23:47.126
<i>It's shaped down so much,</i>
<i>there's metal sticking out,</i>

23:47.126 --> 23:49.211
<i>there's no wood</i>
<i>on the sides of it,</i>

23:49.211 --> 23:50.588
and it's ripping into my pinky.

23:50.588 --> 23:52.840
But the big thing
is the chipping.

23:52.840 --> 23:56.010
I mean, this is 4 inches
of area that's chipped out.

23:56.010 --> 23:58.095
But it stayed straight.

23:58.095 --> 23:59.555
It didn't bend,
and it didn't snap.

23:59.555 --> 24:00.598
Good job.

24:00.598 --> 24:01.765
- Thank you, sir.

24:01.765 --> 24:03.559
- How you feeling, Brian?

24:03.559 --> 24:04.852
- I'm feeling great.
- Cool. Ready to do this?

24:04.852 --> 24:06.228
- Absolutely.

24:06.228 --> 24:08.230
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:08.230 --> 24:10.399
<i>Antler is</i>
<i>a very hard material,</i>

24:10.399 --> 24:13.527
<i>and after seeing</i>
<i>Connor's blade chip like that,</i>

24:13.527 --> 24:15.279
I'm quite nervous.

24:15.279 --> 24:18.407
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:18.407 --> 24:21.285
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:21.285 --> 24:27.207
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:29.335 --> 24:31.003
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:31.003 --> 24:33.130
- All right, Brian, obviously,

24:33.130 --> 24:35.507
we've got chipping
and wrinkled edges here.

24:35.507 --> 24:37.217
- Yep.

24:37.217 --> 24:39.553
- So there is
a heat treat issue, okay?

24:39.553 --> 24:41.347
- Okay.

24:41.347 --> 24:42.848
- But it stayed true,
and it didn't break.

24:42.848 --> 24:43.974
- Good.
- Good job.

24:43.974 --> 24:46.310
- Thank you. Appreciate it.

24:46.310 --> 24:48.979
- Curtis, you ready?
- Go ahead.

24:48.979 --> 24:51.690
- Don't act so excited.
- Go ahead.

24:51.690 --> 24:53.484
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:53.484 --> 24:55.694
<i>Antler is a very,</i>
<i>very hard material.</i>

24:55.694 --> 24:59.114
<i>It may chip the edge.</i>
<i>It may completely destroy it.</i>

24:59.114 --> 25:00.199
Here we go.

25:00.199 --> 25:01.825
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:01.825 --> 25:04.745
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:04.745 --> 25:06.664
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:08.999 --> 25:10.793
- [exhales]

25:10.793 --> 25:12.378
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:12.378 --> 25:14.588
<i>- J. stops, and...</i>

25:14.588 --> 25:16.215
I'm really nervous
about my blade now.

25:16.215 --> 25:17.841
<i>There's definitely</i>
<i>something wrong.</i>

25:26.642 --> 25:28.435
<i>[</i> - Four more.

25:28.435 --> 25:34.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:34.024 --> 25:35.985
[steel resounding]

25:38.570 --> 25:41.865
<i>[solemn music]</i>

25:41.865 --> 25:47.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:47.162 --> 25:50.666
All right, Curtis,
the first thing I wanna say is,

25:50.666 --> 25:52.626
you made a beautiful handle.
- Thank you.

25:52.626 --> 25:55.045
- There's just enough in here
to fill the palm, an index.

25:55.045 --> 25:57.715
I knew where that edge was
every swing.

25:57.715 --> 25:59.925
So fantastic job on that.
- Thank you.

25:59.925 --> 26:02.052
- But we definitely
had an issue

26:02.052 --> 26:04.096
in round one
with the heat treating,

26:04.096 --> 26:05.931
and, I mean, you can tell.

26:05.931 --> 26:07.599
You've got
your forge scale here,

26:07.599 --> 26:10.394
which hides
the stress fracture there.

26:10.394 --> 26:14.231
So, the blade is very brittle.

26:14.231 --> 26:15.733
It just breaks my heart
when stuff like this happens.

26:15.733 --> 26:16.984
- Yeah.

26:16.984 --> 26:19.528
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:19.528 --> 26:22.531
- Well, Curtis, it seems
a flaw from the first round

26:22.531 --> 26:25.367
has thwarted your efforts
here in this competition.

26:25.367 --> 26:27.578
We can no longer
test your blade

26:27.578 --> 26:29.204
due to a catastrophic
blade failure,

26:29.204 --> 26:30.831
and for that reason,

26:30.831 --> 26:32.249
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

26:32.249 --> 26:33.959
<i>[solemn music]</i>

26:33.959 --> 26:36.420
- Very, very disappointed
that I couldn't move on,

26:36.420 --> 26:38.630
<i>but I'm very proud</i>
<i>of the fact that</i>

26:38.630 --> 26:41.717
<i>I was able to complete</i>
<i>my blade in five hours.</i>

26:41.717 --> 26:44.136
<i>I really challenged</i>
<i>myself here.</i>

26:44.136 --> 26:46.764
The ball bearing,
it was made at 52-100 steel.

26:46.764 --> 26:49.308
<i>I've never used that before,</i>
<i>so it's really tough.</i>

26:49.308 --> 26:52.144
<i>But I really didn't</i>
<i>expect it to break.</i>

26:52.144 --> 26:53.437
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:53.437 --> 26:55.773
I'll go see Marc.
[chuckles]

26:55.773 --> 26:57.691
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:00.819 --> 27:02.780
- Connor, Brian,
congratulations,

27:02.780 --> 27:04.156
you guys have made it to

27:04.156 --> 27:06.366
the final round of
this competition.

27:06.366 --> 27:08.327
Now all you need to do is
go back to your home forges

27:08.327 --> 27:11.705
and re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

27:11.705 --> 27:13.040
That weapon is...

27:13.040 --> 27:15.334
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:15.334 --> 27:16.502
The kilij.

27:16.502 --> 27:18.879
- Ah. Okay.

27:18.879 --> 27:20.672
<i>- Originating</i>
<i>in the Ottoman Empire,</i>

27:20.672 --> 27:22.382
<i>the kilij was</i>
<i>one of the region's</i>

27:22.382 --> 27:24.885
<i>most recognizable</i>
<i>and dominant sabers.</i>

27:24.885 --> 27:26.887
<i>Featuring a unique design,</i>

27:26.887 --> 27:29.097
<i>its single-edged blade curves</i>
<i>to a double-edged tip,</i>

27:29.097 --> 27:31.016
<i>creating a hefty</i>
<i>forward weight</i>

27:31.016 --> 27:32.810
<i>that increases</i>
<i>the momentum of the swing,</i>

27:32.810 --> 27:34.728
<i>enhancing its cutting power.</i>

27:34.728 --> 27:36.980
<i>Not only an unparalleled</i>
<i>slasher,</i>

27:36.980 --> 27:39.566
<i>its subtle curve also made it</i>
<i>a powerful thruster,</i>

27:39.566 --> 27:41.318
<i>penetrating deep into an enemy</i>

27:41.318 --> 27:43.195
<i>to produce brutal</i>
<i>and fatal wounds.</i>

27:43.195 --> 27:45.239
<i>The weapon dominated</i>
<i>battlefields for centuries</i>

27:45.239 --> 27:46.532
<i>until it was</i>
<i>eventually replaced</i>

27:46.532 --> 27:48.367
<i>by more Western-type sabers,</i>

27:48.367 --> 27:50.285
<i>such as the Mameluke sword,</i>

27:50.285 --> 27:53.038
<i>which featured a longer,</i>
<i>narrower, less curved design.</i>

27:53.038 --> 27:54.832
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:54.832 --> 27:57.125
The blade must fall within
the following parameters:

27:57.125 --> 27:58.877
<i>The length of the blade</i>
<i>from the tip to the guard</i>

27:58.877 --> 28:01.213
<i>must be between</i>
<i>28 and 30 inches.</i>

28:01.213 --> 28:03.048
<i>The width of the blade</i>
<i>at the guard</i>

28:03.048 --> 28:05.676
<i>must be no less than</i>
<i>an inch and three quarters.</i>

28:05.676 --> 28:07.511
<i>Your blade must have a yelman</i>

28:07.511 --> 28:09.805
<i>that flares wider</i>
<i>than the rest of the blade</i>

28:09.805 --> 28:11.473
and is double-edged.

28:11.473 --> 28:14.101
And your crossguard
must include langets.

28:14.101 --> 28:18.355
<i>- Uh, that's a big-ass</i>
<i>curved blade.</i>

28:18.355 --> 28:20.524
I've never produced
something so curved

28:20.524 --> 28:23.819
or finished something so long.

28:23.819 --> 28:25.946
- Bladesmiths, you'll have
five days at your home forge

28:25.946 --> 28:27.155
to complete this challenge.

28:27.155 --> 28:28.657
At the end of five days,

28:28.657 --> 28:30.033
you'll return
and present your blades

28:30.033 --> 28:31.869
to our panel of expert judges.

28:31.869 --> 28:33.412
And only after
they've thoroughly tested

28:33.412 --> 28:35.080
those weapons
will they declare one of you

28:35.080 --> 28:36.832
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

28:36.832 --> 28:39.543
who also leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

28:39.543 --> 28:41.003
Good luck, bladesmiths.

28:41.003 --> 28:42.838
We'll see you in five days.

28:42.838 --> 28:44.214
- Good luck, man.
- Yeah.

28:44.214 --> 28:47.217
<i>[rock music]</i>

28:47.217 --> 28:49.261
<i>Being back home,</i>

28:49.261 --> 28:51.388
<i>I'm definitely</i>
<i>a little bit more comfortable.</i>

28:51.388 --> 28:53.432
<i>I've never finished a blade</i>
<i>as large as a kilij.</i>

28:53.432 --> 28:55.183
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:55.183 --> 28:57.603
For day one, my plan is

28:57.603 --> 28:59.229
<i>to get this whole blade</i>
<i>forged out.</i>

28:59.229 --> 29:00.939
<i>Doesn't need to be pretty.</i>

29:00.939 --> 29:03.650
<i>It just needs</i>
<i>to get the job done.</i>

29:03.650 --> 29:05.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:05.652 --> 29:08.155
Actually, that is
just straight-up twisted.

29:08.155 --> 29:10.282
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:10.282 --> 29:12.618
If you see it happening,
just straighten it immediately.

29:12.618 --> 29:15.245
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:15.245 --> 29:17.080
Give it some straightening
on the anvil,

29:17.080 --> 29:19.124
and then I'm gonna move
to curving it.

29:19.124 --> 29:22.085
<i>All of this bending,</i>
<i>straightening</i>

29:22.085 --> 29:24.796
<i>could be adding up</i>
<i>stresses into my blade.</i>

29:24.796 --> 29:26.757
[German accent]
"And if it is not up to snuff,

29:26.757 --> 29:29.343
they do not a-help,
not at all."

29:29.343 --> 29:31.345
<i>I am absolutely exhausted.</i>

29:31.345 --> 29:34.640
<i>I'm just gonna go ahead</i>
<i>and call it a day.</i>

29:34.640 --> 29:37.809
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:37.809 --> 29:39.811
- I'm here back at my forge
in Jamesville, New York.

29:39.811 --> 29:42.022
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:42.022 --> 29:44.066
<i>I don't have a power hammer</i>
<i>or a press.</i>

29:44.066 --> 29:45.484
<i>I'm gonna be just</i>
<i>spending a lot of time</i>

29:45.484 --> 29:46.693
with the hammer and the anvil.

29:46.693 --> 29:47.736
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:47.736 --> 29:49.780
There we go.

29:49.780 --> 29:51.281
<i>I wanna get it blocked out</i>
<i>and get it to shape</i>

29:51.281 --> 29:52.366
by the end of the day.

29:52.366 --> 29:57.537
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:57.537 --> 30:00.832
It's just not really going
how I had hoped.

30:00.832 --> 30:02.876
<i>Had a chance</i>
<i>to get the steel hot,</i>

30:02.876 --> 30:04.753
<i>and I'm moving it,</i>

30:04.753 --> 30:07.047
but it's a lot of work
to move it quarter of an inch.

30:07.047 --> 30:08.465
Change of plans:

30:08.465 --> 30:10.133
I'm gonna use
a different kinda steel.

30:10.133 --> 30:11.969
<i>I'm losing</i>
<i>a little bit of time,</i>

30:11.969 --> 30:14.388
<i>but I have to get</i>
<i>a new piece of steel.</i>

30:14.388 --> 30:16.264
<i>Hopefully it works</i>
<i>a little bit better.</i>

30:16.264 --> 30:20.143
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:20.143 --> 30:22.354
- Day two, I'll just be
working on grinding the blade

30:22.354 --> 30:24.314
<i>and getting it ready</i>
<i>for heat treat.</i>

30:24.314 --> 30:27.859
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:27.859 --> 30:29.820
Perfect!
Now it's time to quench.

30:29.820 --> 30:32.280
<i>[tense music]</i>

30:32.280 --> 30:33.782
[mumbling]

30:33.782 --> 30:34.950
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:34.950 --> 30:36.284
Oh...

30:36.284 --> 30:39.079
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:39.079 --> 30:40.789
[blows]

30:40.789 --> 30:43.041
Looks relatively straight.

30:43.041 --> 30:45.627
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:45.627 --> 30:47.004
Wait.

30:47.004 --> 30:48.880
Hasn't hardened really at all.

30:48.880 --> 30:50.674
<i>I need to quench</i>
<i>this blade again.</i>

30:50.674 --> 30:52.259
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:52.259 --> 30:54.177
[muttering]

30:54.177 --> 30:56.138
I'm getting a bit frustrated...

30:56.138 --> 30:57.889
Nope, not satisfied.

30:57.889 --> 30:59.933
...that it hasn't hardened.

30:59.933 --> 31:02.310
<i>Multiple quenches could cause</i>
<i>fractures or warps.</i>

31:02.310 --> 31:05.689
I definitely don't want
to start over again.

31:05.689 --> 31:07.357
Quenching!

31:12.529 --> 31:14.740
Ah! Thank God!

31:14.740 --> 31:16.908
This blade is hard.

31:16.908 --> 31:18.452
Hoo-whee!

31:18.452 --> 31:20.454
Three quenches, three,

31:20.454 --> 31:22.330
before I got
the right temperature.

31:22.330 --> 31:24.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:24.249 --> 31:26.418
I should know better.
I really should know better.

31:26.418 --> 31:28.211
<i>[rock music]</i>

31:28.211 --> 31:29.796
<i>- The steel's here.</i>

31:29.796 --> 31:32.174
<i>I decided to switch over</i>
<i>to the 1070.</i>

31:32.174 --> 31:34.509
<i>It's a lot closer to</i>
<i>the width that I need,</i>

31:34.509 --> 31:37.304
<i>and it's gonna take</i>
<i>a lot less forge time.</i>

31:37.304 --> 31:39.765
I'm ready to rock.

31:39.765 --> 31:42.684
<i>I feel like I'm playing</i>
<i>catchup a little bit.</i>

31:42.684 --> 31:45.312
<i>By the end of today,</i>
<i>I need to have a shaped blade</i>

31:45.312 --> 31:46.938
<i>pretty well profiled</i>

31:46.938 --> 31:48.732
<i>and maybe quenchable</i>
<i>by tomorrow.</i>

31:48.732 --> 31:50.484
It's not heating up
very quickly,

31:50.484 --> 31:52.194
but I feel a lot better
than I did yesterday,

31:52.194 --> 31:54.446
that's for sure.

31:54.446 --> 31:56.656
<i>While I think</i>
<i>it was a bit risky</i>

31:56.656 --> 31:58.742
<i>to kinda switch gears</i>
<i>with the steels,</i>

31:58.742 --> 32:01.703
<i>I think I made</i>
<i>the right decision.</i>

32:01.703 --> 32:04.039
Heat treat tomorrow, for sure.

32:04.039 --> 32:06.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:06.458 --> 32:08.335
<i>- It's day four, and I have</i>
<i>to work on the handle.</i>

32:08.335 --> 32:09.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:09.544 --> 32:12.214
That went super smoothly.

32:12.214 --> 32:14.633
This handle won't fit
underneath the langet,

32:14.633 --> 32:17.010
so I need to carve
a channel out,

32:17.010 --> 32:19.179
so that way it will just slide
straight underneath.

32:19.179 --> 32:22.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:22.140 --> 32:23.683
Yay, it fits.

32:23.683 --> 32:25.268
Everything is tight.

32:25.268 --> 32:28.730
I can move on
to shaping the handle.

32:28.730 --> 32:30.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:30.565 --> 32:33.401
<i>In the knife making round,</i>
<i>my handle was</i>

32:33.401 --> 32:35.821
<i>a little uncomfortable</i>
<i>in J. Neilson's hand,</i>

32:35.821 --> 32:37.364
<i>so I really wanna</i>
<i>make something</i>

32:37.364 --> 32:39.449
<i>that's very comfortable</i>
<i>for him to hold.</i>

32:39.449 --> 32:40.909
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:40.909 --> 32:42.619
Ugh. That's aggravating.

32:44.746 --> 32:46.873
It's just way too square,

32:46.873 --> 32:50.418
and I really have
no good way of fixing it,

32:50.418 --> 32:52.379
'cause the langets

32:52.379 --> 32:55.382
are what set
the maximum thickness.

32:55.382 --> 32:57.175
<i>I'm just gonna</i>
<i>have to accept it.</i>

32:57.175 --> 32:59.177
<i>I just hope it doesn't</i>
<i>come back to bite me.</i>

32:59.177 --> 33:00.720
[sighs]

33:00.720 --> 33:02.597
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:02.597 --> 33:04.224
<i>- Today, I'm gonna start out</i>
<i>with the handle.</i>

33:04.224 --> 33:06.268
<i>I've picked out the wood.</i>

33:06.268 --> 33:09.062
<i>I've got to make sure it fits</i>
<i>comfortably in the hand.</i>

33:09.062 --> 33:11.439
<i>And the other</i>
<i>major component of this</i>

33:11.439 --> 33:14.651
<i>is fitting the langet</i>
<i>into the handle itself.</i>

33:14.651 --> 33:16.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:16.403 --> 33:17.863
<i>Everything's kinda</i>
<i>roughed out.</i>

33:17.863 --> 33:19.739
So far, so good.

33:19.739 --> 33:21.199
If both of our weapons
are kind of similar,

33:21.199 --> 33:22.951
<i>in terms of the testing,</i>

33:22.951 --> 33:24.744
<i>I believe I've got</i>
<i>a bit of an advantage</i>

33:24.744 --> 33:26.413
<i>in terms of how it looks.</i>

33:26.413 --> 33:29.416
Doug should be happy
when he's swinging it.

33:29.416 --> 33:32.544
<i>[tense music]</i>

33:32.544 --> 33:35.463
- Connor, Brian,
welcome back to The Forge.

33:35.463 --> 33:37.048
You've had five days
at your home forge

33:37.048 --> 33:39.009
